{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518285"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:02:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:02:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12905"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12905"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.28,0.24,0.24,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5343"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100859"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5343"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12905"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83281"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1903"},{"type":"tags","id":"2860"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9570"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10010"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13209"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34658"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43370"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100859"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the General Practice (GP) clinic with a 12-day history of pain in his left knee joint. He is having difficulty walking. He has never had something like this before. He is travelling in the area, and usually attends a different GP clinic interstate. He has a medical history of heart failure, hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and myocardial infarction. His medications include furosemide (recently commenced), however he is unsure what else he takes. His last HbA1c was 8.5%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 133/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.1\u00b0C. The left knee is swollen and red, with reduced range of movement. The limb is neurovascularly intact, and there are no visible ulcers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn arthrocentesis and synovial fluid analysis are performed, which show rhomboid-shaped crystals that are positively birefringent. Synovial fluid analysis shows the following results:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC: 41,000 mm\u00b3 (\u0026lt;200)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPolymorphonuclear cells: 51% (\u0026lt;25%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGram stain result is negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests show that calcium, magnesium, urate, and phosphate levels are within normal ranges.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flucloxacillin","Intra-articular glucocorticoids","Colchicine","NSAIDs","Arthroscopic washout"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms consistent with calcium pyrophosphate deposition (CPPD) disease, also known as pseudogout. The diagnosis is confirmed by the presence of positively birefringent rhomboid-shaped crystals in the synovial fluid, which is characteristic of CPPD. The elevated synovial fluid white cell count and percentage of polymorphonuclear cells indicate an inflammatory process, while the negative gram stain makes septic arthritis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColchicine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for this patient. It is commonly used to treat acute flares of CPPD and has multiple mechanisms of action, including disrupting inflammasome action. Colchicine is particularly suitable for this patient given his comorbidities, as it has fewer contraindications compared to other treatment options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENSAIDs\u003C/strong\u003E are often used to treat CPPD, but they would not be recommended for this patient due to his history of heart failure and myocardial infarction. NSAIDs can exacerbate heart failure and increase cardiovascular risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntra-articular glucocorticoids\u003C/strong\u003E can be effective in treating CPPD, but they should be used cautiously in this patient due to his poorly controlled type 2 diabetes (HbA1c 8.5%). Glucocorticoids can worsen glycaemic control. Despite being intra-articular, most of the steroid ends up systemically absorbed. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for treating septic arthritis, but this diagnosis is less likely given the presence of CPPD crystals and the negative gram stain. Antibiotics are not indicated for the treatment of CPPD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArthroscopic washout\u003C/strong\u003E is a surgical intervention typically reserved for septic arthritis. It is not indicated for CPPD, especially when the diagnosis is clear based on synovial fluid analysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing CPPD, it\u0027s important to consider patient-specific factors. This patient\u0027s recent initiation of furosemide (a loop diuretic) may have contributed to the CPPD flare, as diuretics are a known risk factor. The choice of colchicine balances efficacy in treating CPPD with the need to avoid exacerbating the patient\u0027s significant comorbidities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CPPD (also known as pseudogout) is diagnosed based on the presence of rhomboid-shaped crystals which are positively birefringent under polarised light.","Colchicine, NSAIDs, and intra-articular corticosteroids are used to treat acute CPPD, with treatment being based on patient-specific factors."],"references":["Varga Z, Sabzwari SRA, Vargova V. Cardiovascular Risk of Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs: An Under-Recognized Public Health Issue. Cureus. 2017 Apr 8;9(4):e1144. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28491485/","Zhang W, Doherty M, Bardin T, Barskova V, Guerne PA, Jansen TL, Leeb BF, Perez-Ruiz F, Pimentao J, Punzi L, Richette P, Sivera F, Uhlig T, Watt I, Pascual E. European League Against Rheumatism recommendations for calcium pyrophosphate deposition. Part I: terminology and diagnosis. Ann Rheum Dis. 2011 Apr;70(4):563-70. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21216817/","Cowley S, McCarthy G. Diagnosis and Treatment of Calcium Pyrophosphate Deposition (CPPD) Disease: A Review. Open Access Rheumatol. 2023 Mar 22;15:33-41. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10040153/","Ryu K, Iriuchishima T, Oshida M, Kato Y, Saito A, Imada M, Aizawa S, Tokuhashi Y, Ryu J. The prevalence of and factors related to calcium pyrophosphate dihydrate crystal deposition in the knee joint. Osteoarthritis Cartilage. 2014 Jul;22(7):975-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24814686/","Rho YH, Zhu Y, Zhang Y, Reginato AM, Choi HK. Risk factors for pseudogout in the general population. Rheumatology (Oxford). 2012 Nov;51(11):2070-4. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3475980/","Dalbeth N, Tedeschi SK. Calcium pyrophosphate deposition disease moves into the spotlight. Lancet Rheumatol. 2023 Sep;5(9):e497-e499. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38251492/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83281"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12905"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83281"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-27T17:18:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-27T17:19:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5343"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100859"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups",